Few in the industry would dispute the merits of the case, nor
these publishers=E2=80=99 essential need to protect their award-worthy I.P.=
 At the same time, their legal battles with these A.I. firms seem to unders=
core an even graver threat: namely, the apparent dearth of any in-house inn=
ovation to capitalize on, or future-proof their businesses for, a fast-appr=
oaching era in which A.I. is likely to fundamentally alter the ways that ne=
ws is both produced and consumed. Indeed, A.I. is about to become as integr=
ated into our economy as software or mobile technology=E2=80=94its
infinite applications and ubiquity are such that we will likely retire the =
term in a few years, much the same way we no longer bother to say digital. =
In a world where humans will become taskmasters, media leaders need to be a=
s focused on incorporating the technology as they are intent on regulating =
its large language models. Lynch isn=E2=80=99t wrong, but the true existent=
ial threat hasn=E2=80=99t even arrived yet.

=C2=A0

In my recent and manifold conversations with leaders on both the business a=
nd editorial side of the magazine industry, it became clear that these inst=
itutions are seemingly unprepared for the coming A.I. transformation. Even =
the leaders who have admirably managed to grow or sustain their businesses =
thus far seem to now take it on faith that the loyalty of their existing su=
bscriber base will safeguard them against forthcoming changes in distributi=
on, and that even the print product
itself=E2=80=94yes, the print product=E2=80=94might be a bulwark against di=
sruption.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99s a contrarian thesis, to say the least. Nick Thompson, the C.E.=
O. of The Atlantic, has spent a lot of time thinking about the A.I. disrupt=
ion, and told me on a recent episode of The Grill Room that he worries =E2=
=80=9Ca lot about a world in which A.I. disintermediates all or many of
the relationships that we have with our readers. I worry about a world wher=
e TheAtlantic.com goes away. I worry about a world in which maybe email eve=
n changes in such a way that =E2=80=A6 it gets harder to reach individuals,=
 or that it becomes so easy to start a newsletter that summarizes the news,=
 that suddenly there are so many competitors to The Atlantic that our posit=
ion in the market declines.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Thompson=E2=80=99s
response has been to invest in strengthening the relationship with the subs=
criber, which he cites as the motivation for The Atlantic=E2=80=99s recent =
decision to add two print editions each year (from 10 to 12 issues, making =
it a true monthly). =E2=80=9CI should try to develop the strongest direct r=
elationships I can with people where there=E2=80=99s no tech platform and n=
o A.I. platform that can get in the middle of that [relationship],=E2=80=9D=
 he said. =E2=80=9COne of those things is print. We make the
magazine, we put it in the U.S. Postal Service, it gets to your door. So, w=
eirdly, print is kind of a counter-A.I. move.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s worth r=
ecalling that The Atlantic is underwritten, at least in part, by Steve Jobs=
=E2=80=99s estate.

Similarly, when I asked David Remnick, the legendary editor of The New York=
er for the last 27 years, how he thought about this challenge, he held up t=
he latest edition of the print
magazine: =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s about as unmediated as you can get,=E2=80=
=9D he said, almost defiantly. =E2=80=9CAnd we produce not a few of these. =
We do this just about every week of the year, 48 a year.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CA Mug=E2=80=99s Game=E2=80=9D
--------------------

Of course, neither of these men are so naive as to believe that
print alone will safeguard their businesses. These are brilliant guys, afte=
r all. Two decades ago, when Thompson was serving as Remnick=E2=80=99s digi=
tal chief, they adapted The New Yorker to Internet 1.0=E2=80=94which, as Re=
mnick told me, required dramatic =E2=80=9Cpsychological, editorial, and alm=
ost physiological=E2=80=9D changes on the part of the staff. =E2=80=9CAnybo=
dy who tries to predict with any confidence what this business will look li=
ke in 10 years is playing a mug=E2=80=99s game. I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=
=80=99s possible,=E2=80=9D he said.
Thompson, to his credit, was clear-eyed that, =E2=80=9Cif going from 10 iss=
ues to 12 issues is the most important thing I do, you fire me immediately,=
 right? It=E2=80=99s not our principal strategy.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Still, it can be unnerving to hear no real answer to the question beyond pr=
int. Remnick cited the advent of A.I.-generated audio versions of the magaz=
ine=E2=80=99s stories, while noting, =E2=80=9Cadmittedly, that=E2=80=99s ce=
rtainly not the
be all and end all of A.I. and its future.=E2=80=9D Thompson said he and hi=
s team are putting a lot of effort into other ideas, but most of it seems t=
o be around optimizing the existing business=E2=80=94such as determining wh=
en nonsubscribers should hit the paywall. =E2=80=9CShould you be shown just=
 the first 200 words of the article? Should you be shown 300? Should you be=
 shown 100? Should you be shown quotes? Should you be shown summaries? Shou=
ld you be shown excerpts? A lot of our work is going into testing that.=E2=
=80=9D
(Of course, The Atlantic is probably already doing this sort of testing and=
 learning. At any rate, it can.)

=C2=A0

Coincidentally, on the same day the News/Media Alliance lawsuit was filed a=
nd the National Magazine Awards nominees were announced, I found myself in =
an off-the-record meeting with a high-level executive at one of the major t=
ech companies. When asked what was occupying his brain space these
days, he said: =E2=80=9CA.I., A.I., A.I., that=E2=80=99s one, two, and thre=
e.=E2=80=9D Like everyone in his field, he evidenced total clarity about th=
e fact that the new technology would fundamentally change, well, everything=
, and that we were only in the earliest, Motorola DynaTAC 8000X phase of it=
s evolution. I have no doubt that Thompson, Remnick, and their contemporari=
es across the publishing industry have countenanced that fact, but it=E2=80=
=99s not clear that they have any real plan for what to do about
it.=C2=A0

Anyway, for whatever it=E2=80=99s worth, both The New Yorker and New York l=
ed the Ellie nominations this year, with seven apiece. This included nods i=
n the highly coveted =E2=80=9Cgeneral excellence=E2=80=9D category, a disti=
nction they shared with National Geographic, ProPublica, and The Verge. The=
 Atlantic picked up four nominations, one for reporting, two for photograph=
y, and one for
animated illustration ( https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2024/07/=
gambling-everywhere-phone-addiction/678913/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F=
14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6=
c60617da42abd12a ). (The New Yorker=E2=80=99s submission here, for Naomi Fr=
y=E2=80=99s article on Mormon TikTok moms, was far more arresting ( https:/=
/www.newyorker.com/culture/critics-notebook/the-mormon-tiktok-moms-are-all-=
of-us?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&u=
tm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).) The
winners will be announced on April 10. Good luck to all.

As I scrolled through these nominations, I couldn=E2=80=99t help but recall=
 a point that Remnick made proudly. During our chat, he noted that The New =
Yorker employs some 28 fact-checkers to work on its long-form journalism. A=
nyone who has worked at The New Yorker knows the profound value that the de=
partment provides=E2=80=94elevating writers, assuaging lawyers, correcting =
the population of Panama or the maiden name of
Saul Bellow=E2=80=99s fourth wife. And yet this is precisely the sort of fu=
nction that A.I. will simplify, perhaps to the point where a future team wi=
ll manage the software as it passes through dozens of articles all at once.=
 It=E2=80=99s going to be a brave new world, and it may be one that benefit=
s the magazine=E2=80=99s margins, even if it challenges its identity, histo=
ry, and values.

